{"timestamp": "2025-11-28 14:06:10.277058", "event": "llm_start", "prompts": ["System: You are an expert network engineer.\nYour task is to submit the final solution for this network problem based on the diagnosis reported provided.\nCarefully review the diagnosis results and ensure that your submission is accurate and complete.\nYou must strictly follow the submission format and call the submit() tool to submit your solution.\nHuman: Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report\nGoal: assess current network health, detect anomalies, localize faulty device(s), and identify likely root cause(s). No mitigation steps provided — only findings and evidence.\n\nExecutive summary\n- The network shows signs of an OSPF adjacency/LSDB synchronization problem among the core routers (particularly between router_core_2 and router_core_3). This produced transient or partial reachability failures from access hosts to the server/DNS subnet (10.200.0.0/24) in initial automated reachability checks.\n- Server-side connectivity (web servers and DNS) and server-access switch are healthy and can reach each other and the access hosts in manual tests. The issue appears to be OSPF LSA propagation / adjacency instability in the core rather than a failure of the servers or access switches.\n- Devices implicated: router_core_3 (primary), router_core_2 (secondary). Evidence shows at least one adjacency in a non-fully-synchronized state (Loading) and missing/unsynchronized summary LSAs on some routers during checks.\n\nDetailed observations and evidence\n\n1) Baseline reachability scan (automated)\n- Initial reachability snapshot (get_reachability) showed multiple critical failures:\n  - host_1_1_1_1 -> dns_server (10.200.0.2): 4/4 lost (100%).\n  - host_2_1_1_1 -> dns_server and all web_server_0..3: 100% loss (where tested).\n  - host_1_1_1_1 -> host_2_1_1_1: 100% loss.\n- At the same time, web servers and dns_server had full intra-server connectivity (web_server_X <-> dns_server and web_server_X <-> web_server_Y all OK). This points to a problem in connectivity from the access networks to the server network (or a control-plane inconsistency), rather than a server-side problem.\n\n2) Host and switch interface state (get_host_net_config)\n- host_1_1_1_1: eth0 = 10.1.1.2/24, default via 10.1.1.1\n- host_2_1_1_1: eth0 = 10.2.1.219/24, default via 10.2.1.1\n- switch_dist_1_1: br0 = 10.1.1.1/24, eth0 = 172.16.0.7/31\n- switch_dist_2_1: br0 = 10.2.1.1/24, eth0 = 172.16.0.9/31\n- switch_server_access: br0 = 10.200.0.1/24, eth5 = 172.16.0.11/31\n- Core routers (router_core_1/2/3) have the expected /31 IPs on their backbone links (172.16.0.x).\n- Interfaces are up on access and server switches; no physical interface errors reported in the ifconfig outputs.\n\n3) Targeted ping tests (manual)\n- host_1_1_1_1 -> switch_dist_1_1 (172.16.0.7): 0% loss (rtt ~1.4 ms)\n- host_1_1_1_1 -> router_core_1 (172.16.0.0): 0% loss\n- host_1_1_1_1 -> router_core_2 (172.16.0.1): 0% loss\n- host_1_1_1_1 -> switch_server_access (10.200.0.1): 0% loss\n- host_1_1_1_1 -> dns_server (10.200.0.2): 0% loss\n- host_2_1_1_1 -> switch_dist_2_1 (172.16.0.9): 0% loss\n- host_2_1_1_1 -> router_core_1/2: 0% loss\n- host_2_1_1_1 -> switch_server_access (10.200.0.1): 0% loss\n- web_server_0 -> host_1_1_1_1: 0% loss\nSummary: manual pings show successful connectivity across the network in these spot checks. This indicates the failure observed in the reachability scan was intermittent or related to a transient control-plane convergence issue.\n\n4) FRR routing tables (frr_show_ip_route)\n- switch_dist_1_1 routing table includes: 10.1.1.0/24 connected; 172.16.0.6/31 connected.\n- switch_dist_2_1 routing table includes: 10.2.1.0/24 connected; 172.16.0.8/31 connected.\n- switch_server_access routing table includes: 10.200.0.0/24 connected; 172.16.0.10/31 connected.\n- router_core_1/2/3 routing outputs show each router has the backbone /31s and OSPF routes, but there are asymmetries in how routes are installed and in next-hops (see OSPF adjacency details below).\n\n5) OSPF neighbor states and DB status (frr_exec show ip ospf neighbor / show ip ospf database)\n- Multiple neighbor entries show unusual states for a backbone of point-to-point links:\n  - router_core_3 neighbor list contains one neighbor in \"Loading/Backup\" state (neighbor ID 172.16.0.1) — this indicates the adjacency is not fully synchronized and the router is still requesting LSAs.\n  - Several neighbors are showing \"Full/DR\" and \"Full/Backup\" roles on what are expected to be point-to-point links (DR/BDR roles are typically seen on multi-access networks). The presence of DR/BDR on these backbone links is unexpected and indicates either:\n    - OSPF network type is treated as broadcast on links that are effectively point-to-point (or)\n    - The topology or FRR interface configuration results in virtual multi-access behavior.\n- router_core_3's OSPF database (show ip ospf database) summary LSAs include:\n  - 10.1.1.0/24 (advertised by 172.16.0.0)\n  - 10.2.1.0/24 (advertised by 172.16.0.1)\n  - and some /31s\n  Notably, the 10.200.0.0/24 (server subnet) is not present in the summary LSAs on router_core_3's database snapshot. (switch_server_access does show 10.200.0.0/24 connected in its routing table.)\n\n6) OSPF DB synchronization indicators\n- router_core_3's neighbor state of \"Loading/Backup\" and non-zero DB request counters in some neighbor outputs indicate LSAs were still being requested and the LSDB was not fully consistent at the time of capture.\n- This is consistent with the reachability scan behavior (initial failures) followed by successful manual pings (subsequent convergence or partial recovery).\n\nLocalization of the fault\n- Primary suspected device: router_core_3\n  - Evidence: router_core_3 shows a neighbor in Loading/Backup (172.16.0.1 — router_core_2), and its OSPF database snapshot lacks the 10.200.0.0/24 summary LSA (advertised by switch_server_access). This suggests LSAs from the server area were not fully propagated/installed on core_3 at that time.\n- Secondary suspected device: router_core_2\n  - Evidence: asymmetry in the neighbor state for the link between core_2 and core_3: router_core_2's neighbor list shows the adjacency as Full/DR while router_core_3 shows Loading/Backup toward router_core_2 — inconsistent adjacency states between the two ends.\n- Other devices (access switches, server-access switch, web servers, DNS): appear healthy and responsive in direct tests; web servers and DNS show full intra-subnet reachability and can reach access hosts in manual tests.\n\nLikely root cause(s) (diagnostic hypotheses)\n- Primary hypothesis: OSPF adjacency and LSDB synchronization problem between core routers (router_core_2 <-> router_core_3), causing incomplete LSA propagation into parts of the backbone and transient reachability loss to the 10.200.0.0/24 server subnet from some access networks.\n  - Supporting evidence:\n    - \"Loading/Backup\" neighbor state on router_core_3 with non-zero DB request counts.\n    - Missing 10.200.0.0/24 in router_core_3's OSPF summary LSAs at the time of capture, while it is present on the server-access device.\n    - Initial reachability scan showed hosts could not reach servers/DNS (100% loss), consistent with missing route/LSA during that snapshot.\n- Contributing/related possibilities:\n  - Mismatched OSPF network types on backbone interfaces (interfaces treated as broadcast instead of point-to-point) causing DR/BDR behavior where it is not expected. The neighbor outputs showing DR/Backup roles on point-to-point links supports this possibility.\n  - Transient OSPF flooding/convergence delays (timers, interface flapping, or brief packet loss) that caused LSDB inconsistency during the automated reachability run but then recovered for manual tests.\n  - MTU mismatch or occasional packet loss on the backbone links could prevent large LSAs from successfully transferring, leaving neighbors in Loading state until retransmission/timeout — but there is no direct MTU/ifconfig RX/TX error evidence in the snapshots provided.\n- Less likely: firewalling or ACLs blocking ICMP selectively — unlikely because server-side pings to hosts were successful and manual pings from hosts to servers are successful now.\n\nTemporal behavior and confidence\n- The problem appears intermittent / transient: the automated reachability run captured a period of failure (hosts could not reach servers), while manual spot tests thereafter showed successful connectivity. This pattern is consistent with an OSPF synchronization/convergence event that was in progress or unstable at the time of the scan.\n- Confidence:\n  - High confidence that OSPF adjacency/LSDB synchronization issues exist (evidence: Loading neighbor, DB requests, missing summary LSAs).\n  - Moderate-to-high confidence that core router adjacency between router_core_2 and router_core_3 is the main locus of the problem.\n  - Moderate confidence that this explains the transient reachability failures to the server subnet during the observed period.\n\nRelevant data excerpts (key evidence)\n- Initial reachability: host_1_1_1_1 -> dns_server: 100% loss; host_2_1_1_1 -> web_server_0..3: 100% loss.\n- OSPF neighbor (router_core_3): shows neighbor 172.16.0.1 in Loading/Backup state (DB requests pending).\n- OSPF database (router_core_3): summary LSAs shown include 10.1.1.0 and 10.2.1.0, but not 10.200.0.0/24.\n- Direct ping tests (later): host_1_1_1_1 -> 10.200.0.2 (dns_server): 4/4 OK (avg ~3.9 ms), showing connectivity once DB was synchronized or during a healthy interval.\n\nRecommended next diagnostic data to collect (if further analysis is desired)\n- Show full OSPF LSDB on all core routers (router_core_1/2/3) concurrently to compare presence/absence and age/sequence numbers of the 10.200.0.0/24 summary LSA (I did obtain router_core_3 DB; comparing all three would confirm propagation gaps).\n- Show interface OSPF network type and related FRR interface configs on the core links to confirm whether links are configured as point-to-point or broadcast (to validate DR/BDR anomalies).\n- Show \"show ip ospf interface\" on core routers to get timers, network type, and whether any retransmissions or MTU mismatches are flagged.\n- Capture OSPF debug/log around the time of the automated reachability test to see LSA flooding/retransmit behavior and any errors.\n- Repeat a full reachability scan while simultaneously streaming OSPF neighbor/table outputs to capture correlation between route availability and packet loss.\n\nConclusion\n- The primary abnormality is OSPF adjacency/LSDB synchronization instability among the core routers (router_core_2 and router_core_3), resulting in transient loss of route visibility to the server subnet (10.200.0.0/24) from parts of the access network at the time of the automated scan. The server farm and server-access switch themselves appear healthy. The immediate focus for further diagnosis should be OSPF adjacency behavior and interface/network-type configuration on the core backbone links to confirm the root cause., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available."], "metadata": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
